                        </msItem>
                    </msContents>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="codex">
                            <supportDesc material="chart">
                                <support/>
                                <extent><measure unit="folio" quantity="35"> 35 folios, 4 flyleaves
                                        (ff. ii + 35 + ii)</measure>.</extent>
                                <foliation xml:id="modern">Pencilled Arabic numerals inscribed on
                                    the lower-right corners of most a sides.</foliation>
                                <collation>Undetermined due to oversewing. <catchwords>No
                                        catchwords</catchwords></collation>
                                <condition>Handle folios with caution: Beware of extensive tears to
                                    the interleaving, especially at head and tail. Some areas
                                    chipped and abraded at the edges. </condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding notBefore="1800" notAfter="1866">
                                <p>Uniformly bound in <placeName
                                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/70111987008653"
                                        key="place_7008653">Britain</placeName> together with <ref
                                            target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_13827"
                                            ><idno>Indian Drawings 21</idno></ref> for former owner
                                        <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058">
                                        Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                                        (1812–1880)</persName>.</p>
                                <p>Individual folios attached with white cambric strips, with thin
                                    white wove interleaving, and compensation guards of camrbic in
                                    the gutters laminated with heavy-weight, heavily flocked,
                                    European machine-manufactured blue paper, with the same added as
                                    endpapers to the beginning and end. Oversewn on five recessed
                                    cords laced into <material>pasteboards</material>. Edges
                                    untrimmed, with white and black front-bead decorative endbands
                                    sewn at <locus from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> and <locus
                                        from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus>. Covered in half medium
                                    brown goastkin <material>leather</material>, hollow-backed, with
                                    spattered decorated paper sides. without a flap (Type III
                                    binding per Déroche).</p>
                                <decoNote type="binding"><locus from="Spine" to="Spine"
                                        >Spine</locus> pan elas palleted with thick single filllet
                                    lines in blind with thin lines in gold on either side. Lettered:<lb/>
                                    <q xml:lang="en">INDIAN<lb/>DRAWINGS</q><lb/> in gold with a
                                    small paper label underneath numbered <q xml:lang="en">Nº
                                        21></q>.</decoNote>
                            <!--  <p><dimensions unit="mm" type="binding">
                                        <height>402</height>
                                        <width>305</width>
                                        <depth>44</depth>
                                    </dimensions></p> -->   
                                <condition>Handle binding with caution. In fair but stable condition
                                    with extensive abrasion and grain layer delamination of the
                                    exterior leather.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                        <sealDesc>
                            <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                                <p>Rectangular seal impressions, intaglio carved in nasta‘līq script
                                    in two stacked lines, double-ruled, of former owner <persName
                                        role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/73846445"
                                        key="person_73846445">Sir Elijah Impey
                                        (1732–1809)</persName>, dated <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                                        when="1775">1775</date>, along with a regnal year <quote
                                        xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">16</quote> of <persName
                                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/49264990" key="person_49264990"
                                        >George III, King of Great Britain (b. 1738, r.
                                        1760–1820)</persName> reads from bottom upwards:<lb/>
                                    <q xml:lang="fa"> سر ایلاجه ایمپی چیف جستس سنه ۱۶، ۱۷۷۵ <lb/>
                                            (<hi xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" rend="italic">Sir Īlāhah
                                            Īmpī Chīf Justis, sanah</hi> 16, 1775).</q><lb/>
                                    <label>Dimensions:</label>
                                    <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                                        <height>19</height>
                                        <width>26</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                            </seal>
                        </sealDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>The folios originate from different sources, with a majority probbly
                            detached from an album assembled for, or acquired by <persName
                                role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/73846445" key="person_73846445"
                                >Sir Elijah Impey (1732–1809)</persName> in <origPlace cert="high"
                                ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7030776">Calcutta
                                (Kolkata)</origPlace> between <origDate calendar="#Gregorian"
                                from="1774" to="1783">1774 to 1783</origDate>, as per his seal
                            impression on <locus from="3b" to="3b">3b</locus>. Impey served as the
                            first Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of Judicature at <placeName
                                ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1100380">Fort
                                William</placeName>, where he amassed a considerable collection,
                            before he returned to <placeName
                                ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/70111987008653"
                                key="place_7008653">Britain</placeName> and passed away.</origin>
                        <provenance><p>
                                <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                                    key="place_7011781">London</placeName> firm of <persName
                                    role="auc" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/102984934"
                                    key="person_102984934">Harry Phillips (d. 1840)</persName> sold
                                Impey's collection <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1810-05-21">21
                                    May 1810</date>; however, others in India also acquired albums
                                and folios from him both prior to—and possibly after—his return to
                                Britain, so whether this volume sold at that sale, possibly
                                separated from a larger one, remains unclear.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Evidently later obtained by scholar <persName type="standard"
                                    role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/"
                                    key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803–1865)</persName> for
                                his library at Randalls Park, <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011735"
                                    key="place_7011735">Leatherhead</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>After Bland's death, <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                                    key="place_7011781">London</placeName> bookseller <persName
                                    role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/"
                                    key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch (1819–1899)</persName>
                                sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName role="fmo"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"
                                    >Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName>
                                in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866-06">June, 1866</date>,
                                paid in two instalments of £450 and £400, and then moved to <orgName
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552"
                                    >Bibliotheca Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384"
                                    key="place_7010384">Wigan</placeName>. He likely selected and
                                arranged the contents of the parcel and had them bound in two
                                volumes, together with <ref><idno>Indian Drawings
                                18</idno></ref>.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                                    change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName>
                                in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from
                                    <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/"
                                    key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of
                                    Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup"
                                    >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                                    calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName
                                    type="corporation" role="rps"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                                    Library</orgName>, <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                                    key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
